@article{Fiedler2021a,
abstract = {A ssessments of financial risk associated with climate change are increasingly informing decision-making in global capital markets 1-6. Investment managers and advisers are calling for climate-related risk to be factored into investment decision-making 7 and for publicly listed companies to disclose such risks in their financial reports 8. Standard-setting accounting bodies have argued that climate-related risks may be considered to be material, and that financial statements should reflect this 9,10 ; a view shared by corporate regulators 11,12. The Financial Stability Board's Taskforce on Climate-Related Financial Disclosures (TCFD) has set out a high-level framework for disclosing both climate risks and opportunities in financial reports 13 , and governments are beginning to move towards the mandatory disclosure of such risks 14,15. Finally, central banks and supervisory authorities are calling for the integration of climate risk information into financial stability monitoring 16,17 and micro-supervision 18 , in some cases specifically alluding to "challenges in analysing and pricing climate risks" 19. To assess financial risk associated with the physical impacts of climate change, and in particular changes in climate extremes 20 , requires knowledge of climate change across multiple space and timescales. Information from global general circulation models (GCMs) 21 and regional climate models (RCMs) 22 is commonly a key input for examining climate risks (Fig. 1a). A vast array of GCM and to a lesser degree RCM projections are freely available, including many petabytes of data from the Coupled Model Intercomparison Project (CMIP) 23,24 , via the Earth System Grid Federation (ESGF; https://esgf.llnl.gov/). CMIP, which historically provided simulations based on new scenarios about every 7 years is now a rolling programme focused on experiments designed to advance climate science via the sharing and comparing of simulations. Each model in CMIP is rigorously evaluated 21 , and the project as a whole presents a scenario-based 'ensemble of opportunity' or distribution of possible climate futures. While inclusion in CMIP requires the submission of specific simulations 24 , it does not take into account the 'skill' of a model to represent climate phenomenon, when compared to observational data. Further, how independent an individual model is 25,26 or the degree it shares components with other models is not assessed, and two models from one modelling centre can be more different than two models from different countries. Overall, the relative strengths of the models available via CMIP and the ESGF for examining financial risk are not easily identified, even by those within the climate modelling community. The use of climate model information by business is further complicated by the varied time horizons for which climate risk information is sought, which can range from months to decades 27,28 but is typically several years 29-31. The original CMIP protocols focused on simulations that explore how the climate responds to the forcing that increasing atmospheric greenhouse gases and aerosols exert over the twenty-first century, but are now updated to include land use and population change 32. These simulations are designed to examine changes in climate once the predictable 'forced response' becomes large relative to the 'unforced response' associated with natural variability. It typically takes several decades of increasing greenhouse gases before the forced response is large enough to separate from the interlaced contribution of natural climate variability. This makes predictions for how increasing greenhouse forcing affects climate on time horizons of a decade or so very difficult 33. Climate science has responded to these difficulties with climate forecasts on timescales of the next decade or two, initialized using observations for the present day. These examine whether using such observational data as initial conditions for a simulation provides useful predictability 34. Whether they do provide useful predictive skill remains an active area of scientific debate. Importantly, these two types of CMIP experiments-greenhouse gas forced simulations and observationally initialized simulations-are available via the ESGF but provide profoundly different insights into climate risk and on fundamentally different timescales. Using information generated by climate models in business is complex 35,36 and while a business can use data from the ESGF directly, climate service providers (CSPs) 37-42 are developing climate services technologies 43 to support the application of data generated by climate modelling for measuring financial risk (Fig. 1). CSPs, sometimes working in collaboration with asset managers 44 , banks 28 and credit ratings agencies 45 , utilize predictive climate analytics, often Emerging awareness of climate-related financial risk has prompted efforts to integrate knowledge of climate change risks into financial decision-making and disclosures. Assessment of future climate risk requires knowledge of how the climate will change on time and spatial scales that vary between business entities. The rules by which climate science can be used appropriately to inform assessments of how climate change will impact financial risk have not yet been developed. In this Perspective, we summarize the demands by the business and finance community for reliable climate information, and the potential and limitations of such information in the context of what climate models can and cannot currently provide. NATurE CliMATE ChANgE | VOL 11 | FEBRUARy 2021 | 87-94 | www.nature.com/natureclimatechange 87},
author = {Fiedler, Tanya and Pitman, Andy J. and Mackenzie, Kate and Wood, Nick and Jakob, Christian and Perkins-Kirkpatrick, Sarah E.},
doi = {10.1038/s41558-020-00984-6},
file = {::},
