@article{Fu2020,
abstract = {S hort-lived climate forcers (SLCFs) are substances with a relatively short lifetime in the atmosphere compared with CO 2 (ref. 1). They include methane, ozone and aerosols (anthro-pogenic and natural) and their respective impact on clouds 2-5. By warming or cooling the climate, SLCFs also affect the carbon cycle through the climate-carbon feedback loop 6-11. Although there are differences in estimates of the climate-carbon feedback between models, it is a consensus that warming or higher temperature increases atmospheric CO 2 concentration 12 , which is a positive feedback process. A few studies have estimated the influence of aerosol cooling effects on terrestrial carbon cycling, although there are large variations among the results 13-15. In addition, it is understood that the climate effects of SLCFs through the climate-carbon feedback are longer-term compared with their own lifetime 16,17 but quantifi-cation of the timescale of this effect remains limited. In this study, we use the compact Earth system model OSCAR v.2.2 (ref. 18) to evaluate the contributions of SLCFs to the radiative forcing (RF) of CO 2 in 2010 through the climate-carbon feedback. Here, the role of SLCFs is through the direct radiative imbalance they cause and therefore impact on temperature and carbon cycle. Other impacts, for example the impact of aerosols on diffuse radiation , nutrition fertilization and ozone damage are not included. To do so, we proceed in three steps. First, we attribute historical climate change to the RF caused by all anthropogenic and natural climate forcers, as reported by the IPCC in their fifth assessment report 1. Second, we attribute the historical change in atmospheric CO 2 concentration and its RF to fossil fuel (FF) CO 2 emissions, land-use change (LUC) CO 2 emissions and to the climate-carbon feedback. Third, we combine the first two steps to attribute the climate-carbon feedback to the non-CO 2 climate forcers, which include the SLCFs like methane, ozone and aerosols in particular. The 'marginal attribution method' is used here (see Methods). OSCAR is a model of reduced complexity that embeds modules for the terrestrial carbon cycle, the oceanic carbon cycle and the climate system that are all calibrated to reproduce the response of complex process-based Coupled Model Intercomparison Project Phase 5 (CMIP5) Earth system models 18. The carbon cycle in OSCAR consists of two components: ocean and land. The ocean carbon cycle includes the dissolution of anthropogenic CO 2 in the surface ocean and transport to the deep ocean. The land carbon cycle includes the response to change in CO 2 concentration or climate. The model was used in a previous study to investigate another aspect of the climate-carbon feedback 10 and it performs well compared with CMIP5 models in the same '1pct CO 2 ' experiment (a 140-yr simulation with atmospheric CO 2 increasing at a rate of 1% yr −1 from pre-industrial values until concentration quadruples) 19 when calculating the feedback sensitivities (Extended Data Figs. 2-4). The RF attribution itself follows an established methodology that we previously used to quantify the contribution of Chinese emissions of GHG and aerosols to the global present-day RF 20. To illustrate the attribution exercise and the model response to a perturbation of SLCF, we perform an idealized experiment before the main result. We remove 1 yr of the volcano forcing in year 1964, to study the model's responses to this pulse of SLCF, both in intensity and timescale. The responses are calculated as the difference between the simulation without the volcanic SLCF pulse in year 1964 (Rm64) and a control simulation with it (Fig. 1a). It shows that in OSCAR, the effects of a pulse of SLCF on temperature and atmospheric CO 2 concentration are lagging in time behind the pulse duration (Fig. 1b,c). After removing the 1964 volcanic RF, the peak response of global mean surface temperature (GMST) is faster than the peak response of atmospheric CO 2 concentration, with time lag of a few years. Notably, the response of GMST returns to its base level at a faster Short-lived climate forcers (SLCFs) like methane, ozone and aerosols have a shorter atmospheric lifetime than CO 2 and are often assumed to have a short-term effect on the climate system: should their emissions cease, so would their radiative forcing (RF). However, via their climate impact, SLCFs can affect carbon sinks and atmospheric CO 2 , causing additional climate change. Here, we use a compact Earth system model to attribute CO 2 RF to direct CO 2 emissions and to climate-carbon feedbacks since the pre-industrial era. We estimate the climate-carbon feedback contributed 93 ± 50 mW m −2 ($\sim$5%) to total RF of CO 2 in 2010. Of this, SLCF impacts were −13 ± 50 mW m −2 , made up of cooling (−115 ± 43 mW m −2) and warming (102 ± 26 mW m −2) terms that largely cancel. This study illustrates the long-term impact that short-lived species have on climate and indicates that past (and future) change in atmospheric CO 2 cannot be attributed only to CO 2 emissions. NATure CLimATe CHANGe | www.nature.com/natureclimatechange},
author = {Fu, Bo and Gasser, Thomas and Li, Bengang and Tao, Shu and Ciais, Philippe and Piao, Shilong and Balkanski, Yves and Li, Wei and Yin, Tianya and Han, Luchao and Li, Xinyue and Han, Yunman and An, Jie and Peng, Siyuan and Xu, Jing},
