member historical ensembles with CESM1.2.2, we estimate the effect on surface air temperatures of applying latitudinally and seasonally resolved GHG concentrations. We find that the ensemble differences in the MAM season provide a regional warming in higher northern latitudes of up to 0.4&thinsp;K over the historical period, latitudinally averaged of about 0.1&thinsp;K, which we estimate to be comparable to the upper bound (&sim;&thinsp;5&thinsp;% level) of natural variability. In comparison to the comparatively straight line of the last 2000 years, the greenhouse gas concentrations since the onset of the industrial period and this studies' projections over the next 100 to 500 years unequivocally depict a ‘hockey-stick' upwards shape &ndash; it is a collective choice whether the hothouse pathway is pursued or whether we manage climate damages to the SSP1-1.9 equivalent of around 1.5&thinsp;&deg;C warming./p},
