@article{Sarofim2021,
abstract = {Reduced complexity climate models are useful tools with practical policy applications, yet evaluation of their performance and application is nascent. We call for stakeholder-driven development and assessment to address user needs, including provision of open-source code and guidance to inform model selection and application. T he climate community uses computational models to project climate change 1 , but no single model is suited for every situation. A variety of models provides an important diversity of options (Table 1), from comprehensive, high-resolution Earth system models (ESMs) to a simple set of equations that transforms emissions into temperature pathways based on impulse-response functions. In this Comment, we focus on reduced complexity (RC) models, which range from idealized, function-based models that only project global mean temperatures to process-driven models that project multiple variables with regional resolution. Three technical characteristics of RC models make them preferable to complex atmosphere-ocean general circulation models (AOGCMs) for certain applications: (1) computational efficiency, (2) adjustable model parameters and (3) lack of chaotic behaviour (Box 1). Beyond these common characteristics, RC models are diverse: they may include additional end points (such as sea-level rise), geographic resolution or key feedbacks (like permafrost thaw). Beyond their technical characteristics, RC models have key administrative characteristics 2 such as whether the code is open source, if user guides exist, simplicity of the model structure, user-friendliness or computational platform requirements. Relevant administrative or technical characteristics will depend on the application for which the RC model is being used, and the circumstances of the user (Table 2). In an assessment of climate change damages valuation, the U.S. National Academy of Sciences (NAS) provided criteria on the use of RC models that are likely to be pertinent for RC model applications outside of valuation. These criteria include: consistency with scientific understanding of equilibrium climate sensitivity, transient climate sensitivity and transient sensitivity to emissions; emissions pulse adjustment timescales; transparency and simplicity; incorporation of non-carbon dioxide forcings; ability to turn individual components (such as carbon cycle feedbacks) on and off for testing; the inclusion of additional climate end points, such as sea-level rise and ocean acidification; and the capacity to perform uncertainty propagation 3. Higher-complexity RC models better capture some climate characteristics. For example, short-lived aerosol impacts differ from those of well-mixed greenhouse gases because aerosol forcing is predominantly over Northern Hemisphere land masses, suggesting that models permit hemispheric and land/ocean differentiation 4. The Model for the Assessment of Greenhouse Gas Induced Climate Change (MAGICC) has these characteristics 5 , but many RC models do not. Similarly, the adjustment timescale to emissions differs between black carbon and greenhouse gases 6,7 , and multi-century projections require a dynamic ocean to model heat uptake (and sea-level rise) over long timescales 8. On the other hand, developing global warming potential estimates is an application that may suffer from increased complexity. While the inclusion of climate-carbon feedbacks in the calculation of global warming potential may be scientifically more accurate, the increased complexity of this calculation and the resulting reduced transparency has been shown to outweigh the improvement (on the order of 2%) in the final values 9. Generally, for public policy applications, there are trade-offs between simplicity and improved representation of the climate system. Table 1 | Properties of climate computational models Complexity High complexity → reduced complexity Model type AOGCMs/ ESMs EMICs RC Models},
